# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: builder-s-old-measurement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] An **Aframax** vessel is an oil tanker with a deadweight between 80,000 and 120,000 metric tonnes.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] The term is based on the **Average Freight Rate Assessment** (**AFRA**), a tanker rate system created in 1954 by Shell Oil to standardize shipping contract terms.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] Due to their favorable size, Aframax tankers can serve most ports in the world.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] These vessels serve regions that do not have very large ports or offshore oil terminals to accommodate Very Large Crude Carriers and Ultra-Large Crude Carriers.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] Aframax tankers are optimal for short- to medium-haul crude oil transportation.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] Aframax class tankers are largely used in the basins of the Black Sea, the North Sea, the Caribbean Sea, the South and East China Seas, and the Mediterranean.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] Non–OPEC exporting countries may require the use of this type of vessel because the harbors and canals through which these countries export their oil are too small to accommodate the Suezmax or the larger categories.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/aframax] An Aframax tanker carries 600,000 barrels of oil as compared to larger tankers that may carry up to 2 million barrels of oil.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] The vessel's clearance is the distance in excess of the air draft which allows a vessel to pass safely under a bridge or obstacle such as power lines, etc.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] A bridge's "clearance below" is most often noted on charts as measured from the surface of the water to the underside of the bridge at the chart datum Mean High Water (MHW), a less restrictive clearance than Mean Higher High Water (MHHW).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] In 2014, the United States Coast Guard reported that 1.2% of the collisions that it had investigated in the recent past were bridge strikes caused by vessels attempting to pass under structures with insufficient clearance.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] The Bridge of the Americas in Panama limits which ships can traverse the Panama Canal due to its height at 61.3 m (201 ft) above the water.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] New vessels are rarely built not clearing 65 m (213 ft), a height which accommodates all but the largest cruise and container ships.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] The Suez Canal Bridge has a 70-metre (230 ft) clearance over the canal.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/air-draft] The Bayonne Bridge, an arch bridge connecting New Jersey with New York City, undertook a $1.7 billion modification to raise its roadbed to 66 m (217 ft).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-list] The **angle of list** is the degree to which a vessel heels (leans or tilts) to either port or starboard at equilibrium—with no external forces acting upon it.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-list] If a listing ship goes beyond the point where a righting moment will keep it afloat, it will capsize and potentially sink.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-list] Listing is caused by the off-centerline distribution of weight aboard due to uneven loading or to flooding.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-list] By contrast, *roll* is the dynamic movement from side to side caused by waves.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] When a vessel has negative metacentric height (GM) *i.e.*, is in unstable equilibrium, any external force applied to the vessel will cause it to start heeling.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] As it heels, the moment of inertia of the vessel's waterplane (a plane intersecting the hull at the water's surface) increases, which increases the vessel's BM (distance from the centre of *B*uoyancy to the *M*etacenter).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] Since there is relatively little change in KB (distance from the *K*eel to the centre of *B*uoyancy) of the vessel, the KM (distance from *K*eel to the *M*etacentre) of the vessel increases.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] At some angle of heel (say 10°), KM will increase sufficiently equal to KG (distance from the keel to the centre of gravity), thus making GM of vessel equal to zero.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] When this occurs, the vessel goes to neutral equilibrium, and the angle of heel at which it happens is called *angle of loll*.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] In other words, when an unstable vessel heels over towards a progressively increasing angle of heel, at a certain angle of heel, the centre of buoyancy (B) may fall vertically below the centre of gravity (G).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] Angle of list should not be confused with angle of loll.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] Angle of list is caused by unequal loading on either side of centre line of vessel.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] Although a vessel at angle of loll does display features of stable equilibrium, this is a dangerous situation and rapid remedial action is required to prevent the vessel from capsizing.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] It is often caused by the influence of a large free surface or the loss of stability due to damaged compartments.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/angle-of-loll] It is different from list in that the vessel is not induced to heel to one side or the other by the distribution of weight, it is merely incapable of maintaining a zero heel attitude.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] It is the Great Belt route that allows the largest ships.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The limit is a draft of 15.4 metres and an air draft of 65 metres (limited by the clearance of the east bridge of the Great Belt Fixed Link).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The length can be around 240 m and the width around 42 m.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] This gives a weight of around 100,000 metric ton.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] Nevertheless, there are also certain larger ship types plying the Baltic Sea.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] Particularly the so-called *B-Max* crude oil tanker with more than 205,000 tons deadweight (68 m width, 325 m length) and the Maersk Triple E class container ship, 400 m length and 165,000 metric tons deadweight.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The Öresund allows only 8 m draft and is no alternative for large ships.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The shortcut Nord-Ostsee-Kanal allows 9.5 m draft.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] Furthermore, many ports limit ship size.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The iron ore ports of Luleå (11 m, to be deepened to 13 m) and Kemi (10 m) and the large port of Klaipėda (14.3 m to be deepened to 15.4 in the early future) have less draft than Baltimax.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The largest port is Primorsk which has 15 m draft, similar to Baltimax.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/baltimax] The Northern Port in Gdańsk can take the 300,000 ton 15 m draft ships.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] The **beam** of a ship is its width at its widest point.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] The **maximum beam** (BMAX) is the distance between planes passing through the outer sides of the ship, **beam of the hull** (BH) only includes permanently fixed parts of the hull, and **beam at waterline** (BWL) is the maximum width where the hull intersects the surface of the water.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] Generally speaking, the wider the beam of a ship (or boat), the more initial stability it has, at the expense of secondary stability in the event of a capsize, where more energy is required to right the vessel from its inverted position.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] A ship that heels on her *beam ends* has her deck beams nearly vertical.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] Typical length-to-beam ratios (aspect ratios) for small sailboats are from 2:1 (dinghies to trailerable sailboats around 20 ft or 6 m) to 5:1 (racing sailboats over 30 ft or 10 m).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] Large ships have widely varying beam ratios, some as large as 20:1.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] Rowing shells designed for flatwater racing may have length to beam ratios as high as 30:1, while a coracle has a ratio of almost 1:1 – it is nearly circular.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] Where LOA is Length OverAll and all lengths are in feet.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] As catamarans have more than one hull, there is a different beam calculation for this kind of vessel.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] This term in typically used in conjunction with LOA (Length overall).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] The ratio of LOA/BOC is used to estimate the stability of multihull vessels.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] The lower the ratio the greater the boat's stability.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/beam-nautical] The BOC for vessels is measured as follows: For a catamaran: the perpendicular distance from the centerline of one hull to the centerline of the other hull, measured at deck level.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] A **hull** is the watertight body of a ship, boat, submarine, or flying boat.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The hull may open at the top (such as a dinghy), or it may be fully or partially covered with a deck.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Atop the deck may be a deckhouse and other superstructures, such as a funnel, derrick, or mast.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The line where the hull meets the water surface is called the waterline.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] There is a wide variety of hull types that are chosen for suitability for different usages, the hull shape being dependent upon the needs of the design.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Shapes range from a nearly perfect box, in the case of scow barges, to a needle-sharp surface of revolution in the case of a racing multihull sailboat.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] In a typical modern steel ship, the hull will have watertight decks, and major transverse members called bulkheads.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] There may also be intermediate members such as girders, stringers and webs, and minor members called ordinary transverse frames, frames, or longitudinals, depending on the structural arrangement.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The uppermost continuous deck may be called the "upper deck", "weather deck", "spar deck", "main deck", or simply "deck".
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The particular name given depends on the context—the type of ship or boat, the arrangement, or even where it sails.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] In a typical wooden sailboat, the hull is constructed of wooden planking, supported by transverse frames (often referred to as ribs) and bulkheads, which are further tied together by longitudinal stringers or ceiling.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Often but not always there is a centerline longitudinal member called a keel.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] In fiberglass or composite hulls, the structure may resemble wooden or steel vessels to some extent, or be of a monocoque arrangement.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] In many cases, composite hulls are built by sandwiching thin fiber-reinforced skins over a lightweight but reasonably rigid core of foam, balsa wood, impregnated paper honeycomb, or other material.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Perhaps the earliest proper hulls were built by the Ancient Egyptians, who by 3000 BC knew how to assemble wooden planks into a hull.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] At present, the most widely used form is the round bilge hull.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] With a small payload, such a craft has less of its hull below the waterline, giving less resistance and more speed.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] With a greater payload, resistance is greater and speed lower, but the hull's outward bend provides smoother performance in waves.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] As such, the inverted bell shape is a popular form used with planing hulls.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] A chined hull does not have a smooth rounded transition between bottom and sides.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Instead, its contours are interrupted by sharp angles where predominantly longitudinal panels of the hull meet.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The sharper the intersection (the more acute the angle), the "harder" the chine.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] More than one chine per side is possible.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The Cajun "pirogue" is an example of a craft with hard chines.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Benefits of this type of hull include potentially lower production cost and a (usually) fairly flat bottom, making the boat faster at planing.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] A hard chined hull resists rolling (in smooth water) more than does a hull with rounded bilges (the chine creates turbulence and drag resisting the rolling motion, as it moves through the water, the rounded-bilge provides less flow resistance around the turn).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] In rough seas, this can make the boat roll more, as the motion drags first down, then up, on a chine: round-bilge boats are more seakindly in waves, as a result.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Each of these chine hulls has its own unique characteristics and use.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The flat-bottom hull has high initial stability but high drag.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] To counter the high drag, hull forms are narrow and sometimes severely tapered at bow and stern.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] This leads to poor stability when heeled in a sailboat.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] This is often countered by using heavy interior ballast on sailing versions.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] They are best suited to sheltered inshore waters.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Early racing power boats were fine forward and flat aft.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] This produced maximum lift and a smooth, fast ride in flat water, but this hull form is easily unsettled in waves.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The multi-chine hull approximates a curved hull form.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] It has less drag than a flat-bottom boat.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Multi chines are more complex to build but produce a more seaworthy hull form.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] V or arc-bottom chine boats have a V shape between 6° and 23°.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The flatter shape of a 6-degree hull will plane with less wind or a lower-horsepower engine but will pound more in waves.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The deep V form (between 18 and 23 degrees) is only suited to high-powered planing boats.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] They require more powerful engines to lift the boat onto the plane but give a faster, smoother ride in waves.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Displacement chined hulls have more wetted surface area, hence more drag, than an equivalent round-hull form, for any given displacement.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Smooth curve hulls are hulls that use, just like the curved hulls, a centreboard, or an attached keel.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Semi round bilge hulls are somewhat less round.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The advantage of the semi-round is that it is a nice middle between the S-bottom and chined hull.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Typical examples of a semi-round bilge hull can be found in the Centaur and Laser sailing dinghies.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] S-bottom hulls are sailing boat hulls with a midships transverse half-section shaped like an *s*.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] In the s-bottom, the hull has round bilges and merges smoothly with the keel, and there are no sharp corners on the hull sides between the keel centreline and the sheer line.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Boats with this hull form may have a long fixed deep keel, or a long shallow fixed keel with a centreboard swing keel inside.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Ballast may be internal, external, or a combination.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] This hull form was most popular in the late 19th and early to mid 20th centuries.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Examples of small sailboats that use this s-shape are the Yngling and Randmeer.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Midship coefficient (**Cm** or **Cx**) is the cross-sectional area (Ax) of the slice at midships (or at the largest section for Cx) divided by beam x draft.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] It displays the ratio of the largest underwater section of the hull to a rectangle of the same overall width and depth as the underwater section of the hull.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] This defines the fullness of the underbody.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] A low Cm indicates a cut-away mid-section and a high Cm indicates a boxy section shape.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Prismatic coefficient (**Cp**) is the volume (V) divided by LWLx Ax.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] It displays the ratio of the immersed volume of the hull to a volume of a prism with equal length to the ship and cross-sectional area equal to the largest underwater section of the hull (midship section).
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] This is used to evaluate the distribution of the volume of the underbody.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] A low or fine Cp indicates a full mid-section and fine ends, a high or full Cp indicates a boat with fuller ends.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Planing hulls and other highspeed hulls tend towards a higher Cp.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Waterplane coefficient (**Cw**) is the waterplane area divided by LWL x BWL.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] The waterplane coefficient expresses the fullness of the waterplane, or the ratio of the waterplane area to a rectangle of the same length and width.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] A low Cw figure indicates fine ends and a high Cw figure indicates fuller ends.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Use of computer-aided design has superseded paper-based methods of ship design that relied on manual calculations and lines drawing.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] Since the early 1990s, a variety of commercial and freeware software packages specialized for naval architecture have been developed that provide 3D drafting capabilities combined with calculation modules for hydrostatics and hydrodynamics.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/block-coefficient] These may be referred to as geometric modeling systems for naval architecture.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The Builder's Old Measurement formula remained in effect until the advent of steam propulsion.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] Steamships required a different method of estimating tonnage, because the ratio of length to beam was larger and a significant volume of internal space was used for boilers and machinery.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] In 1849, the Moorsom System was created in the United Kingdom.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The Moorsom system calculates the cargo-carrying capacity in cubic feet, another method of volumetric measurement.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The capacity in cubic feet is then divided by 100 cubic feet (2.8 m3) of capacity per gross ton, resulting in a tonnage expressed in tons.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] King Edward I levied the first tax on the hire of ships in England in 1303 based on tons burthen.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] Later, King Edward III levied a tax of 3 shillings on each tun of imported wine, roughly equivalent to £149 in 2025.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] At that time a tun was a wine container of 252 wine gallons, approx 210 imp gal (955 L) weighing about 2,240 lb (1,020 kg), a weight known today as a long ton or imperial ton.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The numerator yields the ship's volume expressed in cubic feet.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] If a tun is deemed to be equivalent to 100 cubic feet, then the tonnage is simply the number of such 100 cubic feet 'tun' units of volume.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] In 1678 Thames shipbuilders used a method assuming that a ship's burden would be 3⁄5 of its displacement.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] This formula remained in effect until the Builder's Old Measurement rule (above) was put into use in 1720, and then mandated by Act of Parliament in 1773.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] itself, at the ship's midpoint, to the top of the uppermost full length deck.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] Interior space; The height from the lowest part of the hull inside the ship, at its midpoint, to the ceiling that is made up of the uppermost full length deck.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] , that is used in context of depth measurement, is usually defined as the uppermost full length deck.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The British took the length measurement from the outside of the stem to the outside of the sternpost, whereas the Americans measured from inside the posts.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The British measured breadth from outside the planks, whereas the Americans measured the breadth from inside the planks.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] Lastly, the British divided by 94, whereas the Americans divided by 95.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The upshot was that American calculations gave a lower number than the British ones.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The British measure yields values about 6% greater than the American.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] For instance, when the British measured the captured USS *President*, their calculations gave her a burthen of 1533+7⁄94 tons, whereas the American calculations gave the burthen as 1444 tons.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] The US system was in use from 1789 until 1864, when a modified version of the Moorsom System was adopted.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] A similar method was used in France to assess the cargo capacity of ships.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] This was standardised in 1681 at 1 tonne burthen per 42 French cubic feet.
[src:builder-s-old-measurement/builder-s-old-measurement] Prior to metrification this unit was called a *port* (from *porter*, transl. to carry) *tonneau* (plural *tonneaux*).
